               <head>Baharistan of Jami</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>1 copy of Bahāristān by Jāmī</summary>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85100085 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85129656 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2008104964" n="1" xml:id="Uk_IO_Islamic_3875-item1">
                     <note>
                        <p>Well known work in verse and prose on Islamic ethics and mystical themes organised into 8 rawz̤ah, written in response to the Gulistān of Saʿdī at the court of the Timurid ruler, Sulṭān Ḥusayn, at Herat </p>
                        <p>Transcribed in very fine calligraphic nastaʿlīq-i khafī; text panels illuminated with fine zar afshānī; decorated double-page opening (ff. 1v-2r) with interlinear taḥrīr, illuminated sarlawḥ and ʿunvān (f. 1v); multiple coloured and gilt rulings (several damaged by corrosion, causing text panels to detach) </p>
                        <p>Not dated or scribe identified in colophon (f. 101v) </p>
                        <p>Neat scholarly corrections and annotations in margins, cropped</p>
                        <p>Owner's seal and inscription (f. 1r): 1) al-ʿabd Niẓām al-Dīn Aḥmad bin Muḥammad [Muq]īm; 2) Allāhu akbar, [dā]khil-i kutub-i faqīr shud, al-ʿabd al-z̤aʿīf Niẓām al-Dīn-i Muḥammad Muqīm ʿafī ʿanhu </p>
                        <p>IOL stamp 17 Nov 1911 </p>
                        <p>Date of possible rebinding: IOL 23 Sep 1914 </p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="per">Persian</textLang>
                     <title xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="work_601">Bahāristān</title>
